About the course
The Psychology Research Internship is different from other courses you have taken thus far in your university career. There are no lectures, no tutorials, and no exam. There is no ‚Äúcontent‚Äù for you to know by the end of the session. You are entirely responsible for your own learning; the more you put in, the more you will get out of this experience. It is a unique opportunity to really use your brain.
PSYC3361 is designed to be a hands-on research experience, but this year we are not going to do that in the lab. We are going to build the course around open data, giving you the opportunity to learn skills that are critical for conducting reproducible research.
By the end of the course you will‚Ä¶
be able to explain why it is important that scientists are transparent about their research practices
be able to use your understanding of structural, ethical and practical barriers to explain describe why some researchers share their data and others don‚Äôt
be able to describe the factors make research analyses more or less difficult to reproduce
be able to apply workflow practices to your own projects in a way that will make transparency and data sharing easy
know enough R to produce descriptive statistics and visualisations in your honours project
It is a bit of a an experiment so we want you to let us know how it is going as we go along. Use this anonymous/editable document at any time to let us know what is working and what is not working.
There will be lots of feedback but no marks (until the end)
The assessment for this course is designed to allow you to engage in activities that research students and academics consider part of their ‚Äújob‚Äù (reading critically, writing code, dealing with data, presenting their work, writing reports, giving feedback to peers, reflecting on their research process). We will give you all Ds and HDs (provided you complete all components and give your best effort), so the numbers don‚Äôt actually matter. You can read more about the grading philosophy for the course in this blog post.
Please come prepared‚Ä¶ it doesn‚Äôt work if you don‚Äôt
The workshops run in flipped mode, much like elective classes in honours. In the first workshop of the term, Kate and I will do most of the talking, but after that the rest of the workshops will be run by you. There will be prep work to do (something to read, watch and/or write) before you arrive. If you do the work, you will be able to contribute to the discussion and engage in the activities. If you haven‚Äôt done what has been assigned for that week, you will let your classmates down.
